<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Burying Stone Tablets With Buddhist Scriptures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 20 (Xinhua) -- A large collection of stone
tablets with Buddhist scriptures carved on them a thousand years
ago will be buried at a Buddhist temple in suburban Beijing to
give them better protection.
</P>
<P>
The 8,000 tablets, out of a total of 10,082, will be put into
underground storage vaults near Yunju Temple, where they were
unearthed 41 years ago, by September 9, 1999, according to Beijing
cultural relics protection officials.
</P>
<P>
The action, the first ever taken in China, aims to protect the
priceless tablets, some of which have already been damaged by air
pollution and inadequate protection methods.
</P>
<P>
The tablets' inscriptions were first made by a senior monk at
Yunju Temple in 605 A.D., and for the next thousand years monks at
the temple continued the work, ultimately transferring 1,122 books
of scriptures onto 1,4278 stone tablets, enough to stretch 12.5
kilometers if they were put end to end.
</P>
<P>
The tablets were buried by the monks in nine caves near the
temple, until they were excavated in 1957.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say that the tablets have great historical, political,
economic, and cultural significance, and for the study of the
development of calligraphy and carving. They are also an important
reference source for collating Buddhist scriptures.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 of the tablets will be put on display at the
temple and the rest will be buried under proper temperature,
ventilation, and moisture controls thanks to new technology in the
underground storage vaults.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
