<HEADLINE> Georgian-Abkhazian Talks Achieve  Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Georgian-Abkhazian talks have
achieved certain progress, the Interfax news agency reported from
Tibilisi, capital of Georgia, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze and Abkhazian leader
Vladislav Ardzinba will meet in the near future and sign documents
on a settlement of the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict, Executive
Secretary of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), Boris
Berezovsky said Friday in Tibilisi.
</P>
<P>
According to Berezovsky, he and Russian First Deputy Foreign
Minister Boris Pastukhov held a meeting with Georgian President
Eduard Shevardnadze on Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
They discussed the draft documents to be signed by the the
Georgian president and Abkhazian leader Vladislav Ardzinba at
their forthcoming meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Friday talks focused on return of refugees to the Gali
district of Abkhazia and economic problems facing the breakaway
Georgian province, Berezovsky said.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting Shevardnadze's letter to Chairman of the Council
of CIS Heads of State, Russian President Boris Yeltsin calling for
an extraordinary CIS summit was also considered.
</P>
<P>
Georgian envoy Vazha Lordkipanidze said though the Georgian and
Abkhazian sides' positions appeared to be closer than before, some
issues remain unsettled. "Work in this direction will be continued
in the next few days," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Abkhazia's economy problems, the Georgian envoy said that
"Abkhazia is an integral part of Georgia and restoration of its
economy is necessary." The region's economic revival should go
hand in hand with return of refugees, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Berezovsky and Pastukhov arrived in Sukhumi on Friday under the
instruction of the Russian president to mediate the
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict.
</P>
<P>
Berezovsky arrived in Yerevan, capital of Armenia, on Saturday
morning for talks over settlement of the Nagorno-Karabakh
conflict.  
</P>
</TEXT>
