<HEADLINE> Iraq Accepts U.N Spare Parts Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced on Saturday that it
accepts a recent resolution of the United Nations Security Council
on buying spare parts for its oil sector.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Foreign Ministry told the official Iraqi
News Agency that "Iraq will deal with the Security Council
resolution No. 1175 of 1998" as a program of action for a period
of 120 days.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution which was passed on Friday, Iraq is
allowed to spend 300 million U.S. dollars of the oil-for-food
program revenues to buy spare parts badly needed in its oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that the resolution should be carried
out on the basis of the 1996 Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program, under
which Iraq is permitted to sell a limited amount of oil every six
months to import food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The program is an exception of the crippling economic sanctions
the U.N. Security Council imposed on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman accused the United States and Britain of trying
to change the temporary and exceptional character of the program
and turning it into a permanent arrangement in an attempt to
prolong the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of some Security Council members, including
Russia, France, China and Brazil for their efforts to eliminate
the political elements that the U.S. and Britain tried to put in
the draft resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
