<HEADLINE> Belgian Donation to Help Rwanda's Balance of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian government has
donated to Bujumbura about one million Belgian Francs to help it
import farming inputs from Belgium backing its balance of
payment.
</P>
<P>
"The fund is specifically for importing agricultural inputs
and equipment manufactured by Belgium industries," the Rwanda
News Agency (RNA) Saturday quoted Jean Sayinzoga, the chairman of
the national task force for the project, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"But the government of Rwanda has to prepare its demand
priorities," Sayinzoga said. The time and place of his remarks
was not given by RNA.
</P>
<P>
However, in the execution, as Sayinzoga said, the local
businessmen will act as middle men of selling inputs to the
farmers and the returns will be reimbursed to the Central Bank of
Rwanda (BNR) to be used by the government for other development
commitments.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen will purchase the said inputs and sell them at
market prices, but the government will subsidize at 50 percent
for the farmers, RNA said in a dispatch to Xinhua based here.
</P>
<P>
The project is within the bilateral cooperation between Rwanda
and Belgium and the discussion on the fund started in late 1990,
modified in 1993 and the bilateral agreement was reached at the
end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The national task force for the management of the project
involves the ministry of commerce, industry and cooperatives (as
the responsible ministry), ministry of agriculture, ministry of
foreign affairs, ministry of finance and economic planning,
chamber of Commerce and Belgian chief of the cooperation mission
in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"Is that a strategy by the Belgium government to clear its
stocks?" asked one Rwandan businessman who preferred to remain
anonymous.
</P>
<P>
But an official in the ministry of agriculture praised the
project as "a support toward the government initiative to improve
agricultural production."
</P>
<P>
Already for 1998 budget, the government of Rwanda has
allocated one billion Rwanda Francs (about 3.4 million U.S.
Dollars) for importing fertilizers and other agricultural inputs
to be sold to the farmers at subsidized prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
