<HEADLINE> Long Way to Go for Angolan Peace: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo Dos
Santos said here Saturday that there is a long way to go for
final peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
But the government is making active efforts to put the peace
process onto the right track again, Dos Santos told reporters at
the Luanda International Airport before leaving for a 48-hour
visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan president asserted that people will soon see
encouraging development of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process hit snags when the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) refused to turn the
four central "sensitive areas" over to the governance of the
government.
</P>
<P>
If UNITA does not take concrete measures to change this
situation, the new sanctions against it adopted on June 12 by the
U.N. Security Council will be in effect on June 25.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he made the trip after the crisis facing Angola's
peace process has been resolved, Dos Santos said tension remains,
but his government, together with the U.N. observers, and even
the opposition UNITA movement, are trying hard to put the peace
process in the right direction again.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan president will begin his visit to Russia on June
22, at the head of a delegation which includes chief officials
from the ministries of foreign affairs, defense, mineral
resources and interior.
</P>
<P>
During his trip in Russia, Dos Santos will sign with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin a declaration on bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also sign accords on promotion and
protection of investment and the exemption of visa processing for
diplomatic and service passports as well as pacts on the joint
exploration of diamonds and on the economic and trade
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
