<HEADLINE> 18 Injured in Clash Between Pro and Anti-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen people were injured, three
of them seriously, during a brief clash Saturday afternoon between
demonstrators protesting the recognition by France of the 1915
genocide of Armenians by Turkey and those who staged a
counter-demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Police said that one man was stabbed in his belly during the
clash which took place in front of the Invalides military museum
in central Paris.
</P>
<P>
The Union of Turkish Associations in France had called for a
demonstration to protest the recognition by the French National
Assembly last month of the genocide of Armenians, which Turkey
denies.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 demonstrators gathering before the OInvalides clashed
with 60 to 80 people staging a counter-demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Police questioned 34 people as suspects or witnesses when most
of those who staged a counter-demonstration descended into the
subway station nearby.
</P>
<P>
Paris shelters the second biggest Armenian community in France
after Marseille.
</P>
<P>
The French National Assembly has formally recognized that from
one million to 1.3 million Armenians were massacred by Turkish
troops in 1915 when they were forcibly removed from their homes
from Turkey to Syria.
</P>
<P>
Turkey says only 300,000 Armenians died when they were
resettled in Syria under the Young Turkey government during World
War I.
</P>
<P>
Turkey accused the Armenians of supporting Russia, which fought
Turkey in the war.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
