<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-20 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urged to Undertake Initiative on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
has urged U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to intervene
personally to reduce military tensions in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Annan, a copy of which obtained here Saturday,
Clerides asked him to "undertake a personal initiative" in line
with a U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Security Council resolution 1146 of 1997 calls upon all
concerned to contribute to a defense spending cut and the
reduction of foreign troops on the island as a way to restore
confidence between the rival Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in 1974
after a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The president said the resolution "offers a sufficient
framework" for a discussion on the security of the island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides urged everybody to "consider how implementation of the
resolution 1146 may be achieved."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated in his letter his "commitment to reconsider the
issue of non-importation on new weapons systems to Cyprus" if
progress is made towards the demilitarization of the island.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been running high on the island since January last
year when Cyprus ordered the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles and greatly angered the Turkish Cypriot side and Ankara.
Cyprus said the deal can only be reconsidered with a progress
regarding the demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
The president recalls his letter of December 1993 to the then
U.N. chief which outlined a detailed proposal for the total
demilitarization of Cyprus, a proposal which Turkey and the
Turkish Cypriot side have turned down.
</P>
<P>
That proposal calls for the disbandment of Greek Cypriot
National Guard and Turkish Cypriot armed forces, as well as the
withdrawal of Turkish forces from northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said that "I have continuously called for a
substantive discussion with the Turkish side along these lines."
</P>
<P>
Clerides' letter to Annan came following a week-long
tit-for-tat show of force between Greece and Turkey, the strong
supporters of Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots respectively.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, four Greek F-16 fighters and two C-130 military
transport planes landed at the newly-completed Paphos military
air base in Cyprus, which was constructed under a joint defense
pact between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey sent six F-16 fighters Thursday to the Turkish
Cypriot-controlled northern Cyprus in retaliation, and five
Turkish navy warships also visited Wednesday the ports of Kyrenia
and Famagusta in the north.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies, have long been at odds
over this strategic island,  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
