<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Turkish Energy Minister Cumhur Ersumer started a
visited to Egypt on Saturday to discuss with the Egyptian side the
export of Egyptian gas to his country.
</P>
<P>
An agreement in this respect is expected to be signed during
the visit of the Turkish official.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait has formed a committee to secure the
implementation of World Trade Organization (WTO) deals, said an
official statement issued on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The committee, grouping representatives of some ministries,
authorities and the private sector, will be chaired by Minister of
Commerce and Industry Abdel Aziz Dekheel Al-Dekheel.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Kuwait is keen on highlighting the
trade reputation, adding that it has joined one of WTO's key
agreements -- the international property deal-- and has set up a
committee to draft a law on protecting intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey and Canada Friday signed an agreement on
social security.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Turks living in Canada and Canadians
living in Turkey will enjoy pensions rationally in each of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
It will provide help to the people who are eligible for
Canadian or Turkish pensions that they have earned when they live
in either of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It will also help avoid situations that Turks living in Canada
or Canadians living in Turkey have to contribute to the social
security systems of the two countries for the same work.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Some German industrial companies have formed a bloc
to pressure the German government to reconsider the relations with
Iraq, local El-Gomhuria daily reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The bloc was formed according to the desire of the companies to
press the German government to adopt a humanitarian and fair
attitude towards Iraq that suffers from international economic
sanctions, visiting Chairman of the German Oil Company Rockel
Frans said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that representatives of 26 German firms have
planned to visit Baghdad in July to seek ways of cooperating with
Iraq in business regardless of the embargo on the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq used to import farm equipment, machines, vehicles, trucks
and other goods from Germany, Iraq's major trade partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
