<HEADLINE> Belgium Coach Blames Team for Early Relaxation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BORDEAUX, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Belgian coach George Leekens said the
2-2 draw with Mexico was mainly due to the early relaxation of the
team after leading 2-0 in the game on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We were 2-0 up and we perhaps counted too much on our lead. Our
attitude changed and we lost two points," Leekens said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "We deserved a better result after leading 2-0. With our
experience I believed we should have coasted through. But a match is
never finished until the whistle."
</P>
<P>
"The players lost four kilos out there. It was very hard to play
football. Some signalled after only 10 minutes that they were
exhausted, they wanted to come off," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said with only two points from two games, the team must win
their last group match against South Korea next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"For the next match we must win. That is our job. In the meantime
we must drink a lot and recover our weight," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mexian coach Manuel Lapuente said, "It was a hard-fought match. It
was very tough with the sending off that meant we had to play ten men
against 11."
</P>
<P>
"We suffered a lot and then it got a bit more balanced. We took a
point away. Of oucrse we would have preferred three," he added.
</P>
<P>
Belgian midfielder Enzo Scifo said, "Conditions were unbelievable.
We led 2-0 and I found the Mexicans seemed down and out. We were right
in the match and we just could not lose it."
</P>
<P>
Scifo added after Gert Verheyen made the foul in the 55 minute to
draw a sending off and a penalty for Mexico, things all changed.
</P>
<P>
"We could have gone 3-0 up. Instead, we let in a goal and lost a
man. After that it got very difficult. With the heat I suffered a lot
in the last 20 minutes," he said.
</P>
<P>
The temperature on the pitch in the Stade Lescure was apparently
above the forcasted 37 degrees centigrade and the Belgians gradually
waned after 10 minutes into the second half. 
</P>
