<HEADLINE> Iraqi Minister Calls for Early Initiation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Minister of Finance Hikmat
Mizdan Ibrahim Saturday called for efforts to open the country's
free trade zone early, hoping it will help revive its economy
badly crippled by the eight-year-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He made the call in his address before the first meeting of
board of the proposed zone which includes representatives of the
ministries of trade, industry, minerals, oil, transport, and
communication as well as the Central Bank of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Ibrahim highlighted the need of exerting more
efforts to finalize the phase of the final work systems of the
free trade zone in Khor Azzobair, south Iraq, and working out the
final shape of the rates of rent allowances, the Iraqi News Agency
(INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister pointed out the necessity of preparing the
areas allocated for buildings and facilities in the zone.
</P>
<P>
The INA report said the board of the free trade zone has
received offers from Asian and Arab countries for investment in
the zone.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decided last year to open Khor Azzobair, Basra province
overlooking the Persian Gulf, for foreign trade in an attempt to
revive its economy which suffers great difficulties due to the
UN-imposed economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
The embargo was imposed in 1990 after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
