<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: A Blow to Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 20 (Xinhua) -- "Tremendous blow to peace."
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu stuck the label on the
current efforts of the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) to
upgrade its status at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
But this very remark can be the most proper to describe
Netanyahu's Jerusalem expansion plan which was endorsed last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Israel will construct a road around East
Jerusalem, build a tunnel under Mount Scopus to connect with
Maaleh Adumim, one of the biggest Jewish settlements in the city
and take steps to attract more Jews to it.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu termed the plan as "a basic change in Jerusalem's
status which will be remembered as a turning point."
</P>
<P>
"The first thing we are doing is to link Greater Jerusalem.
The second thing is strengthing the Jewish majority in Jerusalem,"
he said, claiming the city as the sovereign capital of Israel, and
only of Israel.
</P>
<P>
These remarks run against nothing but the Oslo Accords.
</P>
<P>
According the Oslo Accords, Jerusalem's status, along with
other thorny issues, should be negotiated in the final status
talks between the Palestinians and Israel. Each side should
refrain from any unilateral actions leading to the change of the
legal status, demographic composition or character of the city
before the talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem in the
1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
The greater Jerusalem plan also coincides with increasing
Jewish settlement activities in the city, holy to Muslims,
Christians and Jews, and intensified Israeli efforts to demolish
Palestinian houses.
</P>
<P>
As for the settlement activities, Palestinian officials have
said the Israelis are trying to create a fait accompli in an
attempt to predetermine the status of Jerusalem before the final
status talks.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the key mediator for the Palestinian-Israeli
peace process, condemned Israel's acts.
</P>
<P>
During a telephone call with Netanyahu Friday, U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright expressed displeasure with the plan.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin dismissed the plan
as "extremely provocative," saying it could inflame violence in
the region.
</P>
<P>
It is "hard to understand" why Israel has taken such a step at
"a sensitive time" in negotiations with the Palestinians, Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on the Israeli troop pullback are stalling
over Israel's refusal to hand over 13 percent of the West Bank to
the Palestinians as suggested by Washington. There are also
reports of signs that Netanyahu might accept the proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0024 </DOCNO>
