<HEADLINE> Arab League Hails EU's Support for Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Ahmed
Esmat Abdel-Meguid Saturday expressed welcome to European Union's
stance on the Arab and Palestinian cause in the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"I consider this stance is very supportive of the Arab and
Palestinian stance," Abdel-Meguid said in an interview with
Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on a statement issued by the EU at the end of
a summit in Britain, which voiced "very grave concern" over the
stalemate in Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The EU, the biggest donor to the Palestinians, called on Israel
"to recognize the right of the Palestinians to exercise
self-determination, without excluding the option of a state."
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid, who has just returned from a week-long visit to
Britain, said that during his stay in London, he held talks with
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook on the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"I told British officials that recent Israeli government
decisions (related to the Mideast) adversely affect the entire
peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The whole Mideast region will be gripped by tension and
plagued by violence if Israel sustains its (intransigent) policy,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said London has assured him it will continue its
efforts to seek ways to advance the peace process after it hands
over the rotating EU presidency to Austria on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League chief said that during his visit in Britain, he
also met with Jim Swire, representative of the families of the
British victims in the Pan Am flight explosion over Lockerbie,
Scotland in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Two Libyans are suspected of masterminding the blast.
</P>
<P>
He discussed with Swire ways and means of breaking the freeze
shrouding the West-Libya crisis over the blast.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain insist that the two Libyan
suspects be tried in either of the two countries. Libya, fearing
that its nationals can not receive fair trial, insist that they be
tried in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
The families of the British victims have reportedly inclined to
agree to the Libyan proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
