<HEADLINE> Pakistan Refuses to Open Trade With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has refused to open
trade with India and called for settling the core issue of Kashmir
between the two countries first.
</P>
<P>
India had repeatedly requested the Pakistani government for a
free trade between the two countries, while pledging all other
disputes will be taken up afterwards, diplomatic sources was
quoted as saying by the independent News Network International
(NNI) Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, through the
Foreign Office, had conveyed it to India that it will give
priority to the amicable settlement of rifts including Kashmir
prior to opening trade, NNI said.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Commerce Ministry told NNI that free trade
between Pakistan and India was not feasible, saying that Indian
industries enjoy subsidies and incentives which are not available
to Pakistan's.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Our government's priority is to resolve other major
differences with India and in the presence of issues like Kashmir
we cannot think for a free trade."
</P>
<P>
The official said that the Foreign Office has issued clear
instructions to relevant authorities not to expand trade and sign
investment treaty with India as long as long-standing issues are
not resolved.
</P>
<P>
According to NNI, a number of Indian firms tried to start joint
industrial ventures here, but the Board of Investment did not
encourage them due to the government policy.
</P>
<P>
Trade figures show that Pakistan maintained 244 million U.S.
dollars deficit in trade with India in the past three financial
years, NNI said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
