<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khmer Rouge Defectors Appeal for National Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Five senior Khmer Rouge
technocrats who defected to the Cambodian Royal Government earlier
this month appealed Sunday for national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference held at Royal Phnom Penh Hotel,
the defectors said that the past should be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
The five men, including Chan Youran, Mak Ben, In Sopheap, Kor
Bun Heng and Thiounn Thieounn, arrived in Phnom Penh on Saturday
after spending years in the jungle since 1994.
</P>
<P>
They have met with Second Prime Minister Hun Sen and First
Prime Minister Ung Huot since Saturday, but details of their
meetings were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the defection, Chan said, is to bring peace to
Cambodia. "No more war in Cambodia. We want national
reconciliation," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the defectors do not know the whereabouts of the
remaining three senior Khmer Rouge leaders -- Ta Mok, Noun Chea
and Khieu Samphan -- since they left them two months ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Chan said: "We think Khieu Samphan is a moderate
leader. Many people believe he could defect to the government."
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen has said on Thursday that his government would welcome
Khieu Samphan if he handed over Ta Mok and Noun Chea to Phnom
Penh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
