<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Approves Jerusalem Expansion Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite U.S. criticism and
protests, the Israeli cabinet Sunday approved a controversial plan
to expand Jerusalem's municipal authority over eight Jewish
settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which was approved after a five-hour debate in the
cabinet, would create an "umbrella authority" over West Bank
settlements surrounding Jerusalem to the north, south and east.
</P>
<P>
It intends to put the settlements under the city's authority
mainly for construction and planning.
</P>
<P>
Any construction in settlements normally should be approved by
the Israeli Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
have strongly condemned the plan. U.S. officials have described it
as "extremely provocative," saying it could inflame violence in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has said that Israel was unilaterally annexing West
Bank land, changing the status of Jerusalem and altering the
geographical structure of the city.
</P>
<P>
Under agreements signed between the Palestinians and Israel,
issues about Jerusalem should be negotiated in the final status
talks for a final peace agreement. Before that, the two sides
should refrain from any unilateral actions to change its status,
demographic composition and other characteristics.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want to establish an independent state in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip with Arab East Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The PNA said the expansion will allow Israel to swallow 18
percent of the West Bank land. It has officially filed a complaint
with the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Israel, however, has said it would not change the status of
Jerusalem and has no intention to annex Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu dismissed the U.S.
and PNA criticism as "ridiculous." He said the U.S. was
"misreading reports in the news media."
</P>
<P>
The plan will also extend Jerusalem's boundaries westward into
Israel itself, annexing several suburbs in a bid to expand the
city's economic base. This has also caused much controversy among
residents in the west of the city.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Israelis demonstrated at Mevasseret Zion, a
community in the west of Jerusalem, protesting the proposed
annexation of their suburbs, which they said would raise their
taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
