<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Achieves Progress in Economic Aid to Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China's policy of mobilizing inland
provinces and municipalities to support economic development in
the Tibet Autonomous Region has achieved remarkable success.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the Tibet Autonomous Region has
carried out 62 capital construction projects funded by 33
departments of the Chinese Central Government and 15 provinces and
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
Total investments in the projects reached 3.67 billion yuan, up
dramatically on the 2.38 billion yuan outlined in the original
plan.
</P>
<P>
The wide-ranging projects involved agriculture, water
conservancy, energy, communications and telecommunications,
industry, social welfare and municipal engineering.
</P>
<P>
The 60 completed projects are not only having a positive
effect on improving the investment environment and local
infrastructure, but also on improving the living standards of
local people.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the aforementioned 62 key projects, central
government departments and 15 cities and municipalities are
undertaking 600 projects with contracted investments of well over
800 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The region has attracted more than 600 engineers and
technicians from the industrial, agricultural, medical and
educational sectors in other provinces and municipalities across
the country over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Various provinces have also helped train some 1,870 Tibetan
technicians.
</P>
<P>
The extensive effort has enabled Tibet to achieve rapid growth
over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The region's 1997 gross domestic product hit 7.7 billion yuan,
with the region's annual economic growth rate for the past three
years surpassing the national rate.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 farmers and herdsmen have escaped poverty,
with the per capita income of urban residents rising by 60 percent
and rural residents by 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has gained an extensive self-development capacity and is
rapidly establishing basic conditions for introducing the
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the central government has provided Tibet
with investments and financial aid totalling 40 billion yuan since
the 1950s, with more than 18 billion yuan provided since 1987
alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
