<HEADLINE> AL Welcomes U.S. Stance on Israeli Plan on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) Sunday hailed
Washington's criticism of an Israeli plan to extend Jerusalem
municipal authority over eight Jewish settlements in the West Bank
and urged stern actions from the key mediator of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department Sunday called the plan, which aimed
to tighten Israel's clamp on Jerusalem, a "provocative" step
adopted at a sensitive time when efforts are exerted to revive the
long-stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Egypt's Middle East News Agency,
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid termed the U.S. reaction
as "strong, decisive and positive," but he added that the Arabs
are "not accustomed to" such U.S. position and open criticism of
the Israeli conduct.
</P>
<P>
He urged the U.S., which has long been criticized by the Arab
world as leaning toward the Jewish state in the Mideast
peace-making, to adopt further such stances regarding the Israeli
practices.
</P>
<P>
"Such Israeli acts provoke both the Arab world and the
international community raising concerns over the future of the
Mideast peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid appealed to the U.S., in its capacity as a sponsor
of the peace drive, to commit to such stances which are greatly
welcomed by the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, defending Israel's
plan as an effort to strengthen the Jewish majority in Jerusalem,
said Sunday U.S. criticism of the Israeli plan was "ridiculous."
</P>
<P>
After a five-hour debate, the Israeli cabinet approved Sunday
the plan unveiled by Netanyahu Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli plan would create an "umbrella authority" over the
West Bank settlements surrounding Jerusalem to the north, south
and east. It intends to put the settlements under the city's
authority mainly for building and planning.
</P>
<P>
Any construction in settlements normally should be approved by
the Israeli Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The plan will also extend Jerusalem's boundaries westward into
Israel itself, annexing several suburbs in a bid to expand the
city's economic base. This has also caused much controversy among
residents in the west of the city.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem in 1967 and later annexed it in
a move that has failed to win international recognition. The
Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of a future
state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deadlocked for 15
months over Israel's settlement building in East Jerusalem and
long-delayed withdrawal from the West Bank. Israel has rejected a
U.S. initiative on further redeployment, which has been accepted
by the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
