<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barren Land Turned into Green Fields in China's Dry Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Green vegetation is emerging in
the most arid and impoverished areas in northwest China's Gansu
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Dingxi area, which has long been known as a place lacking
the basic conditions for human subsistence, has suffered a
deteriorating ecology and frequent natural disasters. A survey
conducted in the mid-1980s showed that the area had 80 million
tons of eroded soil annually, accounting for 17 percent of the
province's total.
</P>
<P>
The local government developed a comprehensive plan to tackle
the problem by planting trees and building terraced fields in some
small valleys of 5-to-50 square kilometers in the early 1980s. The
area has successfully rehabilitated 110 small rivers and lakes,
and has listed another 280 for consideration.
</P>
<P>
The air quality has improved, say local farmers, who also
expressed satisfaction with cash crops that once could not be
planted in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party secretary of the Hongxian Village Branch
said that turning hillsides to terraced fields makes it possible
to increase per-hectare wheat output by 3,000 kilograms. And, as a
result, the villagers' annual per-capita income reached more than
900 yuan, a three-fold increase over 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Livestock farming has become the area's key industry with the
recovery of the vegetation, contributing 35 percent to local
economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Mideast Envoy to Visit Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 21 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Special Envoy
to the Middle East Miguel Angel Moratinos is expected to visit
Lebanon Wednesday in new efforts to revive the peace negotiations
on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The EU envoy will hold talks with Lebanese leaders over the
latest developments in the region, especially on the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks in the peace process with Israel, the Orient radio
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Israel and Syria and Lebanon were
broken off after Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu came to
power in June, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu refused to hand back to Syria the strategic Golan
Heights which Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East war and
asked to restart the talks from the scratch.
</P>
<P>
But Syria, who says Israel's former Labor government agreed
to hand back the Golan Heights, wants to resume the talks from
where they were left off.
</P>
<P>
Although Israel formally endorsed in April the 20-year-old
U.N. Resolution 425 which calls for an unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon, it conditioned the withdrawal
on security guarantees from the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria have rejected the offer and demanded
again that Israel restart negotiations simultaneously with Syria
and Lebanon from where they suspended. Syria now has some 40,000
troops in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Moratinos will present fresh ideas to
Lebanese leaders in a bid to revive the peace talks in the
Lebanese and Syrian tracks in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He is now in Damascus where he held talks with Syrian leaders
over his ideas.
</P>
<P>
He will also go to Tel Aviv following his visit to Beirut and
discuss his proposals, which have not been disclosed, with Israeli
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
settlements from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attack.
</P>
