<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Establish Solar Energy Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Solar Energy Industries
Association of Zimbabwe (SEIAZ) is setting up a renewable energy
funding conjunction with the government and other agencies under
which companies and end-users would access funds for solar
projects.
</P>
<P>
SEIAZ Chairman Bulukani Masola said in an interview Saturday
the sector faced scepticism from some financial institutions
about its potential, hence the need for a fund, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of our financial institutions don't really understand
the importance of this sector and we believe it will take a long
time before most people realise that this is the energy of the
future," he said.
</P>
<P>
The association, he said, needed about 100 Zimbabwean Dollars
(5.5 million U.S. Dollars) for capacity building and end user
financing.
</P>
<P>
There would also be a component that renewable energy be used
for commercially viable projects in agriculture, specifically in
irrigation, refrigeration of vegetables, poultry and fisheries,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The rising cost of electricity, he said, was a boon for the
industry and the end user would benefit from a cheaper source of
power.
</P>
<P>
Support for the renewable energy sector is increasing with
over 40 companies now involved in the manufacture, distribution
and installation of solar equipment, said the chairman.
</P>
<P>
The photovoltaic equipment, a non-polluting energy technology
which converts sunlight into electricity, is used for lighting,
solar water heating and wind-base generators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
