<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rearing Fur-Bearing Animals Becomes Popular in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Rearing fur-bearing animals has
become one of the main businesses for Chinese farmers to earn
extra money.
</P>
<P>
Information from a recent national symposium on development
strategy for fur-bearing animals disclosed that about one million
minks are reared in China, while the foxes and racoon dogs bred
amount to 1.5 million head.
</P>
<P>
Researcher Yang Fuhe, who is also secretary-general of the China
Special Products Society, said, "Comparing to North Europe and
North America, China is late in starting to rear fur-bearing
animals. But It has become the largest market of fur-related
products in the wake of economic development and improvement in
Chinese people's living standards, which has brought forth
opportunities for rearing such animals in the country."
</P>
<P>
Artificially-reared fur-bearing animals in China mainly include
minks, foxes and racoon dogs, which are mostly grown under cold
weather. They provide 90 percent of the raw materials needed by
the world's fur processing industry.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 million pieces of mink furs and 14 million pieces
of fox furs are consumed globally each year.
</P>
<P>
The rearing of fur-bearing animals was on an adequate scale in
China in the 1950s, and by the mid-1980s China had formed a
capacity of exporting five million pieces of mink furs annually.
But the rearing of such animals slumped in the early 1990s as
export fell.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, domestic demand for fur-related products
has been increasing, so the rearing of fur-bearing animals has
again recovered. Moreover, China has become a major importer of
fur raw materials and products in the world since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the symposium urged more efforts to improve the
quality of the breeding stock, furs, and the fur processing
technology in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ministry of Agriculture has entrusted the Special
Products Institute of the Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences
to build a center for monitoring and testing breeding stock
varieties of special economic animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
