<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Parliament Impeaches Interior Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative-dominated
Majlis (parliament) on Sunday impeached Interior Minister Abdollah
Nouri by refusing to give him a vote of confidence, dealing a
serious blow to the moderate government of President Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the Majlis open session on Nouri's impeachment
motion raised by 31 conservative Majlis deputies, 137 voted for
the motion, 117 against and 11 abstention.
</P>
<P>
Nouri's failure to win a vote of confidence indicated the
continued control of the conservatives on the Iranian Majlis,
hinting more difficulties facing the open-minded Khatami's
government in the future.
</P>
<P>
Nouri was accused of creating tensions in the society, issuing
provocative statements and using inexperienced persons for the
managerial posts at the Interior Ministry. He was also blamed for
his open support for Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, who
has been under open trial since June 7 on graft charges.
</P>
<P>
Khatami and his moderate supporters strongly supported Nouri,
even warning that Nouri's absence from the cabinet would be
detrimental to the government of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the conservatives said that the continuation of
Nour's service as interior minister would be dangerous to the
tranquility and stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
Khatami would be forced to choose a new interior minister to
replace Nouri. Some moderates have hinted that former Interior
Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi would be Khatami's choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
