<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harbin International Trade Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The international trade fair in
Harbin, capital of Northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, ended
today with contracts valued at over 4.5 billion US dollars, up 34
percent on last year's event.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang Deputy Governor Wang Zhenchuan reported that the
figure included commodity trade deals valued at 2.4 billion US
dollars and over 1.1 billion US dollars in contracts for economic
and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The fair also attracted well over 900 million US dollars in
foreign investment contracts, up 19 percent on the 1997 figure,
according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,200 companies from both at home and abroad, including
Tsingtao Beer, Nestles and Siemens, exhibited products during the
seven-day fair.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government also inked intergovernmental
cooperation agreement with government delegations from 13
countries, including Russia, Canada, Japan, Poland, the Republic
of Korea, Yugoslav, Italy and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
