<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Seeking Business With Iraq Under Oil-for-Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian firms are seeking big
business with Iraq under the framework of the United Nations
oil-for-food program, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA)
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During a visit by an Egyptian economic delegation to Baghdad
last week, Egyptian firms offered to participate in schemes to
renovate Iraq's dilapidated oil facilities and prospect for new
fields. Iraq and Egypt also clinched several deals to increase
Egyptian food and medical exports to Iraq, which is suffering
under the U.N. sanctions, the MENA said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian delegation was headed by Egyptian Trade and Supply
Minister Ahmed Gowaili, who held talks with Iraqi Oil Minister
Amir Rashid.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Iraqi side asked Egypt to provide its
factories with necessary spare parts, raw materials and Egyptian
expertise to upgrade their productivity.
</P>
<P>
Rashid welcomed the Egyptian private sector's participation in
Iraq's oil sector's overhaul, adding that 300 million U.S. dollars
had been earmarked out of the oil-for-food program revenues to buy
badly needed spare parts to develop this industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program struck in 1996, Iraq
is permitted to sell a limited amount of oil every six months to
import food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
The program is an exception to the crippling economic sanctions
the U.N. Security Council has imposed on Iraq after its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Egyptian Holding Company of Pharmaceutical
Industries Galal Ghorab told MENA Sunday that Egypt will export to
Iraq 3.5 million pounds (1.03 million dollars) worth of medicines
in July within the fourth stage of the oil-for-food deal according
to the memo of understanding signed by the two ministers in
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has already exported medicine and medical equipment worth
45 million Egyptian pounds (13.2 million dollars) to Iraq through
the previous three deals since the inception of the oil-for-food
deal, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the recent deal signed in Baghdad, Iraq agreed to import
150 million dollars worth of foodstuffs from Egypt in the later
half of this year, the food import will increase to 250 million at
the end of next year, Sunday's Egyptian Gazette reported.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian delegation representing a large group of heads of
pharmaceutical companies will leave for Baghdad next week for
talks with Iraqi Health Ministry officials on the government's
programs to rehabilitate hospitals and dispensaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
