<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Increasing Efforts to Promote Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The government of Guangdong
Province, China's economic powerhouse, has issued a notice
recently calling for stronger support to foreign trade and
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Local financial departments should be responsible for the 20
percent of export tax refunds turned in to the central government,
the notice said.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong will set up a low-interest fund for exports, make new
efforts to establish state-owned holding companies in the
foreign trade sector, and give priority to them in terms of
being listed on stock exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
It will continue to promote businesses engaged in processing
materials supplied by overseas customers, and exempt state- and
province-approved such foreign trade firms of value added tax. It
will offer some preferential taxation policies to foreign-funded
ventures that are engaged in processing overseas-supplied
materials.
</P>
<P>
The province is working out policies to encourage the private
sector to do foreign trade, providing that private businesses will
enjoy the same rights as the state sector in using overseas
investments in terms of export licenses and quotas.
</P>
<P>
Being China's largest experter, Guangdong registered more than
130 billion US dollars worth of imports and exports last year,
accounting for 40 percent of the nation's total. It used 14.2
billion US dollars worth of foreign investment in the same year,
making up 22 percent of the national total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
