<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Chinese Being Encouraged to Fully Tap Potential (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Wang Yumei, a young rural woman
from east China's Shandong Province, quit her job at a hostel
owned by the county government in 1991 much to the chagrin of
fellow villagers who thought she had lost a "golden opportunity".
</P>
<P>
However, Wang, 25, is now the president of a rabbit breeding
company with total capital of 56 million yuan (6.7 million US
dollars) and annual profits of close to seven million yuan.
</P>
<P>
"I earned a pretty good income at the hostel seven years ago,
but was convinced that raising rabbit was a good way to make more
money and help my fellow villagers escape poverty," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government advocates that all Chinese young people
emulate Wang's pioneering spirit and unwillingness to be
content with the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Hu Jintao spoke at last Friday's opening session
of the 14th National Congress of the Communist Youth League of
China (CYLC) and urged young people to maintain a pioneering
spirit and exhibit creativity while making painstaking efforts
to adapt to economic and social changes.
</P>
<P>
Delegates attending the congress pointed to Wang's success as
an inspiration to a large number of young workers laid-off from
state-owned enterprises in cities.
</P>
<P>
Young people under the age of 35 account for some 35 percent of
China's nearly 10 million laid-off workers, with the rate for
state-owned enterprises approaching 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese people had cradle-to-grave jobs under the former
planned economic system, and many young workers with great
potential were relegated to posts requiring minimal expertise,"
according to Xi Zhenhui, a CYLC official with the Beijing Textile
Holding Company.
</P>
<P>
"Young laid-off workers are temporarily without jobs, but at the same
time have an excellent opportunity to exhibit their potential," said
Xie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Youth Urged to Fully Tap Potential (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Many companies in China's slumping textile industry have be
forced to reduce staff and destroy spindles to cut losses. Some
50,000 textile workers in Beijing have lost their jobs over the
past five years, according to Xie.
</P>
<P>
He said the traditional function of youth league organizations
in enterprises centers on uniting and guiding young people to make
more contributions to their enterprises and the country.
</P>
<P>
"However, as part of ongoing economic restructuring, the work
of the CYLC should focus on encouraging laid-off young workers to
be independent and self-supporting, while at the same time helping
them tap their potential and start anew," said Xie.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Qiang, member of the Secretariat of the 13th CYLC Central
Committee, noted that the major tasks of the CYLC organizations at
all levels are to help young people develop new concepts of
employment suited to the market economy, and to both search for
and create posts which give full play to the many advantages
offered by young people.
</P>
<P>
The CYLC Central Committee recently launched a program to train
highly capable young workers with pioneering awareness and provide
assistance enabling them to establish small- to medium-size
enterprises to provide employment for other laid-off
contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
The committee has raised over 10 million yuan for a fund that
helps young people launch new undertakings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
