<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Saudi Arabia Call on Israel to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Defense Minister of Saudi
Arabia Prince Sultan Ibin Abdul-Aziz Sunday urged Israel to submit
to the requirements of peace in order to advance the stranded
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Aziz, who is also Second Prime Minister and Inspector
General, made his remarks after talks with visiting Lebanese
Defense Minister Mohsen Dalloul Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
The prince was quoted by Saudi Press Agency Sunday as saying
that the current crisis in Arab world were caused by Israel's
reluctance to comply with the requirements and principles of the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi defense minister said his talks with Dalloul were
characterized by the spirit of fraternity and cordiality which
marks the Lebanese-Saudi relations.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Dalloul said Lebanon had no problem in signing a
peace treaty with Israel if it was a just and comprehensive one.
</P>
<P>
"If Israel wants peace and security, then we (Lebanon) and
Syria are ready to sign a peace accord within three months
provided it is based on the principles of justice as stipulated by
the Madrid peace conference," Dalloul said.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States was interested in this approach
because Washington was aware of the dangers which could result
from the collapse of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
During a recent visit to the United States, Lebanese Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri had announced the readiness of both Lebanon
and Syria to sign "a just and comprehensive peace accord" with
Israel within three months.
</P>
<P>
Dalloul, who arrived in Saudi Arabia Saturday for talks on
ways to enhance bilateral ties, also reiterated Lebanon's
appreciation for the Saudi support to Lebanon and the efforts to
restore peace and stability to Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
