<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Grape Producer Expects Good Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Heavily laden grapevines indicate
the sixteenth consecutive good grape harvest for Turpan
Prefecture, China's leading grape producer located in the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
"The vineyard is my bank, and my savings deposit will surely
grow this year," said Rozi Niyaz, a Uygur farmer in Lianmuqin
Township, Shanshan County.
</P>
<P>
Rozi's half hectare of grapevines are once again thriving, and
his family earned more than 60,000 yuan last year on the same
tract of land. Grape farmers in the township earn an annual per
capita income of 2,100 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Turpan will harvest over 400,000 tons of fresh grapes this year
on 16,000 ha, and will process 80,000 tons of raisins, according
to local grape expert Li Zhichao.
</P>
<P>
Turpan, a popular tourism venue famous for its seedless grapes,
has a history of 2,000 years of grape cultivation. Farmers in the
cities harvested 1,700 kg of grapes per hectare in 1997, compared
with a mere 200 kg in the 1950s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
