<HEADLINE> Iranian Majlis Speaker Says Impeachment Nothing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Majlis (parliament) Speaker
Nateq Nouri Sunday rejected the accusations by the moderates that
the hardliners wanted to capitalize on the impeachment of Interior
Minister to weaken the government.
</P>
<P>
At the open session of the Majlis to debate over impeaching
Abdollah Nouri, the speaker said that the impeachment did not mean
contradiction and confrontation between the legislative and
executive departments, nor did it imply any attempt to undermine
the government led by President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The request for impeachment is part of the rights of parliament
members and such motions were also seen before, he said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing unity, the speaker also said that the government and
parliament have one outlook and "I have recommended my colleagues
to act like before to demonstrate their maturity in a healthy and
clam atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
Nouri appeared at open session Sunday to defend his
performance, refuting the accusations leveled against him by 31
hardline lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
At the session, the lawmakers once again accused him of
creating tensions in the society, giving provocative statements
and appointing inexperienced people to managerial posts in his
ministry.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that the continuation of Nouri's service as the
interior minister is detrimental to tranquillity and stability in
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the Majlis regulation, lawmakers will cast the
no-confidence vote against Nouri at the end of the debate in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The impeachment of the moderate Nouri came at a time when
relations between moderate government and hardliners in judiciary
and parliament became tense since the arrest and trial of Tehran
mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, who was also a loyalist of the
president.
</P>
<P>
The moderates have termed the moves launched by the hardliners
as attempts aimed at weakening Khatami's government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
