<HEADLINE> French Government Confident of HK's Future (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Trade between France and Hong Kong remains steady year after
year, at a level of around 20 billion French franc (3.3 billion
U.S. dollars) of French exports, mainly involving aircraft,
consumer goods, wine and electronics, one third of which are
re-exported.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the visit last March to France by Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa, Dana said it was remarkable in many
respects. Tung was received at the highest levels, both by French
President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
The visit gave the chief executive a unique opportunity to
explain in detail how Hong Kong had developed after the handover,
especially in terms of the respect for the principle of a high
degree of autonomy written down in the Basic Law, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It was a special occasion for the highest authorities in
France to understand how well those principles had been respected
in reality," he added.
</P>
<P>
Dana noted that the most significant feature of the relations
between France and Hong Kong has been steady development of
France's presence here over the years.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 French people are currently living in Hong
Kong. It is France's second largest community in Asia after Japan.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 French companies are operating in Hong Kong, and
some of the biggest have set up regional headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
A specific proof of the confidence of the French government
in the future of Hong Kong is also the extension of the French
International School whose capacity should reach 1,600 places
around year 2001 compared with 1,000 at present.
</P>
<P>
"The promotion of France in Hong Kong both as a tourist
destination and as a place to invest in is, of course, one of our
main objectives," Dana said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
