<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Currency Accounts Allowed in Pakistan Under </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of Pakistan has
allowed opening of new foreign currency accounts with permission
to withdraw in any foreign currency from Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources from the Central Bank, both resident
and non-resident Pakistanis are allowed to open foreign currency
accounts under the new rules introduced by the bank Saturday
through a circular.
</P>
<P>
The authorized dealers will no longer be required to surrender
the foreign currencies to the State Bank.
</P>
<P>
And the State Bank will not provide exchange risk guarantee.
The banks and depositors will be free to use the funds as they
please and banks will decide the rate of return that they will
offer to the depositors.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that these new foreign currency accounts will
enjoy the immunity as protection provided in the Protection of
Economic Reforms Act, 1992.
</P>
<P>
No new accounts will be opened under the old scheme nor any
fresh credit made into the existing accounts except
interest/profit and items in transit on May 28, 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the existing non-resident foreign currency accounts of
overseas Pakistanis can receive fresh remittances, which can be
withdrawn in rupee at the special rate of 46 rupees per U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
After Pakistan's detonation of five nuclear devices on May 28,
President Rafiq Tarar promulgated a decree, announcing a temporary
freezing of all foreign currency accounts and stopping of free
movement of foreign currency in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
