<HEADLINE> Museveni Angry over Bad Defense Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
is extremely angry over senior army officers' purchase of
out-of-date military equipment from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
A Sunday Monitor report said the second-hand MI24 helicopter
gunships bought from Belarus, a former Soviet Union republic,
were in such bad conditions that military pilots refused to fly
them, sending the president hitting the roof with anger.
</P>
<P>
The military is also reported to have bought five pieces of
100 mm anti-aircraft guns from the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea which have also been found not to be up to scratch.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the government had released 12.2 million U.S.
Dollars for the purchase of helicopters while the actual money
spent on the same gunships by the purchasers was only 5.4 million
Dollars, leaving the rest as the purchasers' commission, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Pinto, a member of parliament from Kakuto, told
parliament Thursday that these officers should be charged with
treason, because they had undermined the national security.
</P>
<P>
Museveni has appointed a commission led by Major Noble
Mayombo, the deputy director of military intelligence, including
experts from the air force, Civil Aviation Authority and a female
officer from the Ministry of Justice to investigate the status of
the gunships.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters, the report said, should have been overhauled
or refurbished before delivery as agreed.
</P>
<P>
The two helicopters already delivered were said to be not air
worthy because the specifications on the logbooks are different
from those on the engines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
