<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mobile Phone Business Develops Rapidly in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The mobile phone sector is now one
of the fastest growing sectors in Bangladesh, said The Bangladesh
Observer weekly reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At present, over 50,000 Bangladeshis are using mobile phones,
according to official estimates.
</P>
<P>
Mobile phone made its first formal entry in this South Asian
country in 1989 when the Citycell company was given license for
cellular phones by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Citycell monopolized the business for several years and
kept the price quite high, which only a few people could afford.
</P>
<P>
That monopoly ended in late 1996 when the government permitted
three more companies -- Aktel, Grameen Phone and Sheba Telcom --
into the business. From then on, the number of cellphone users has
kept increasing owing to the lower price.
</P>
<P>
Besides, this has also put pressure on the state-owned
Telegraph &AMP; Telephone (T&AMP;T), which had until then the monopoly
over the telephone service.
</P>
<P>
The T&AMP;T has currently nearly 500,000 subscribers, up from
65,000 in 1971, the year of Bangladesh's independence.
</P>
<P>
Yet the T&AMP;T is swamped with hundreds of thousands of
applications seeking telephone lines. Those who can afford up to
15,000 taka (about 326 U.S. dollars) are now opting for mobile
phones instead of waiting for phones from the T&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
Even some of the rural poor have now access to mobile phones
thanks to the Grameen Phone company run by the Grameen Bank, which
has earned international reputation for providing small loans to
the poor women in villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0108 </DOCNO>
