<HEADLINE> Clinton Interviewed by Chinese Reporters-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said that his upcoming visit to China will help deepen the mutual
understanding and expand the cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope in a roundtable discussion here on Friday
with a group of U.S.-based Chinese journalists.
</P>
<P>
The president said, "I hope that through my trip both I and the
people of the United States will learn more about China -- about
the rich history, about the exciting events going on today, about
the incredible potential for the future of the Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that through his trip "the leaders and the people
of China will learn more about the United States".
</P>
<P>
"I hope we can expand the areas of cooperation between our
governments and our peoples," the president, who begins his China
tour next Thursday, told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
As home to one-fourth of the world's people and with a rapidly
growing economy, he said, China has enormous contributions to make
to the world of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said China and the United States should be partners for
stability and security in Asia.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China recently led the five-party talks on the
situation in South Asia and played a positive role in preventing a
nuclear race in that region.
</P>
<P>
Asked about his vision on the constructive partnership between
China and the United States in the 21st century, Clinton indicated
that the partnership also includes that on preventing arms
proliferation, on the fight against crimes, on energy and
environment, on science and technology, on economy and on
promoting peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
He added that developing and improving this cooperation will
not only benefit the people of the two countries but also help
stabilize the world.
</P>
<P>
Talking about U.S. critics of his China policy, Clinton said
that most Americans support his engagement policy because they
want a constructive partnership with the government and the people
of China.
</P>
<P>
"I have to say in this case, I think my critics are wrong," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe most Americans understand that we have differences
now and 100 years from now we will have some differences, because
we are different people with different cultures and different
systems and different backgrounds," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I think the important thing for the Congress is to
recognize that over the long run we must choose engagement with
China, not isolation from China, not estrangement from China."
</P>
<P>
"Once you make that decision," Clinton went on, "then the
question is how can you expand the areas of cooperation where we
can agree, how shall we manage our disagreements, and how can we
learn from one another so that we can build a more peaceful, more
prosperous, more open world."
</P>
<P>
"Even my harshest critics would have to admit that President
Jiang and I have had wonderful, stimulating and very honest
discussions about our differences."
</P>
<P>
"It seems to me that the idea that we should have less contact
with China, with the Chinese government and with the Chinese
people, is just wrong," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said he will continue to stick up to his China policy and do
his best to defeat any legislation in the Congress that would
undermine the ability of his government to pursue the interests of
the U.S. and the interests of the American people in developing a
partnership with China and the Chinese people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
