<HEADLINE> Iranian Parliament Opens Impeachment Debate on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian parliament, the Majlis,
opened the debate Sunday over impeaching Interior Minister
Abdollah Nouri, a representative of the moderate movement who is
under strong fire from the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Nouri appeared at the Majlis open session to defend his
performance, refuting the accusations leveled against him by 31
conservative parliamentaries, who have tabled the no-confidence
vote against him.
</P>
<P>
At the Majlis open session, broadcast live by Tehran Radio,
conservative lawmakers once again blasted Nouri for creating
tensions in the society, giving provocative interviews and
speeches in different provinces and appointing inexperienced
people to managerial posts at the interior ministry.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that the continuation of Nouri's service as the
interior minister is detrimental to tranquillity and stability in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Majlis' session was adjourned at noon and will continue in
the afternoon. According the regulations, the Majlis will cast the
no-confidence vote against Nouri at the end of the debate.
</P>
<P>
To close their ranks for Sunday's showdown, Majlis deputies of
the two rival camps held separate meetings Saturday to coordinate
their stance.
</P>
<P>
The moderate daily Iran News reported Sunday that this was an
indication that the conservative lawmakers have no intention to
back down from their impeachment offensive against Nouri.
</P>
<P>
But the daily predicted a victory for Nouri in the
no-confidence vote, citing that he is enjoying the solid support
of the moderate president Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Nouri's fate is relying on the vote of independent Majlis
deputies, because there is a balance of power between the moderate
and conservative camps with each having around 100 seats in the
270-seat Majlis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
