<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Invest Heavily in Highway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China will pour an investment of
160 billion yuan (about 19.28 billion US dollars) to build
highways this year, 40 billion yuan more than original allocation
of 120 billion yuan (about 14.46 billion US dollars) or up 33.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
And the combined investment for highway construction will reach
500 billion yuan (about 60.24 billion US dollars) by the year
2000, Minister of Communications Huang Zhendong told a national
conference on highway construction called in Fuzhou Saturday.
</P>
<P>
To accelerate the pace of highway construction is an important
decision made by the State Council, China's highest governing
body, as part of the efforts to meet the domestic demand and ensure
the economic growth this year, Huang stressed.
</P>
<P>
Building of key highway projects will cost 90 billion yuan
(about 10.84 billion US dollars) this year. Upgrading of road
network and construction of major highway hubs will cost 50
billion yuan (about 6.02 billion US dollars). Another 20 billion
yuan (about 2.41 billion US dollars) will be used to build county
and township roads and highways.
</P>
<P>
The country will add more than 24,000 km of highways in 1998,
including 1,117 km of expressways, Huang said, adding that the
highway building will provide 3.25 million job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
From 1998 to the year 2000, China will build 74,000 km of
highways, including more than 3,200 km of expressways. By the end
of this century, the country will have more than 1.3 million km of
highways and more than 8,000 km of expressways.
</P>
<P>
According to Huang, the country will give priority to the
construction of "two vertical, two horizontal, and three important
highways", which refer to Beijing-Zhuhai, Tongjiang-Sanya,
Lianyungang-Horgas, Shanghai-Chengdu, Beijing-Shenyang,
Beijing-Shanghai, and Chongqing-Beihai highways, respectively, in
the coming three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
