<HEADLINE> U.S. Reaffirms Commitment to Advancing Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. has assured the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) of its commitment to
advancing the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, Israel Radio
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright expressed the
message in a letter to PNA President Yasser Arafat delivered by
U.S. Consul-General John Herbst of Jerusalem during their meeting
Saturday night in the West Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Albright said that the U.S. will not give up its
efforts in achieving a resolution from Israel on the second
redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Herbst reviewed the latest status in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and proposals by Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on further withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has proposed to combine the second and the third
phases of the pullback from West Bank into one with a total scope
of 15 percent. Palestinians have rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted PNA sources as saying that the message came
amid increasing doubts among Palestinian leaders over
Washington's commitment to pressing Israel to accept a U.S.
initiative aimed at breaking the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal, which has been accepted by the PNA,
reportedly calls on Israel to hand over 13.1 percent more of the
West Bank to the Palestinians during its second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians have been
stalled since March last year when Israel started to construct
Jewish settlement in the Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
And the talks were deeply stranded due to Israel's
intransigence over its troops redeployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
