<HEADLINE> Nigeria: 14 Feared Killed in Fresh Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 21 (Xinhua) -- No fewer than 14 persons were
feared dead with 24 others wounded following a riot Saturday
sparked off allegedly by extortion by a soldier in Ibadan, the
largest city in western Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, six policemen alleged to have shot the spare parts
traders have been arrested, press reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Eye witnesses were quoted as saying that the trouble started
when one of the team of soldiers and mobile policemen guarding
the Agodi prison went to a nearby spare parts selling point where
he picked quarrel with a trader over a commission of about 22
cents.
</P>
<P>
The solider, said to be ostensibly offended by the trader's
refusal, got into a fit of anger and fired the man in the hip,
leaving him in a pool of blood while firing sporadically into the
air to ward off a mob that had gathered.
</P>
<P>
While other traders arrived at the scene, intending to carry
the victim to hospital, other "trigger-happy" soldiers went into
shooting spree, gunning down more than eight persons on the spot,
the Sunday Punch reported.
</P>
<P>
Infuriated by this action, militant youths stormed the Agodi
police station and made a bonfire of old tyres preventing access
to the building.
</P>
<P>
At least 14 persons were picked up dead, while 24 others had
gunshot wounds, with 20 placed on danger list.
</P>
<P>
The police that has confirmed "disturbances" in that area and
is investigating the incident has appealed to the traders to be
calm, promising that all the policemen involved would be dealt
with accordingly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
