<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 07:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Protests Killing of Religious Leader in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran has lodged a strong protest to
Iraq against the assassination of a Shiite religious leader in
southern Iraq, Tehran radio reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry summoned Iraqi Charge d'Affaires Saleh
Noori Samarmad in Tehran on Saturday night and expressed the
protest.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Director General for Persian Gulf affairs Ali
Aghsar Hojji was quoted as saying the Iraqi government has the
responsibility to ensure the security of life and properties of
Iranian citizens in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He urged Baghdad to take necessary measures to punish those
responsible for the killing of Ayatollah Sheikh Mirza Ali Gharavi
and his relatives in Najaf area.
</P>
<P>
Ayatollah Gharavi, one of his sons, son-in-law and driver were
shot by unidentified gunmen Thursday night on the way to Najaf
from Karbala after the pilgrimage at the holy shrine of the Shiite
third Imam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
On April 22, another well-known Shiite religious leader
Ayatollah Boroujerdi was also gunned down in the Shiite holy city
of Najaf.
</P>
<P>
Hojji warned that the repetition of such incidents would damage
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Samarmad expressed regret over Thursday's killing, saying that
he would inform the Iraqi government of Iran's stance and give
relevant answer to Iran.
</P>
<P>
An Iran-based Iraqi Shiite opposition group Saturday accused
Baghdad of being behind the murder, alleging that Iraq's
intelligence service opened fire at Ayatollah Gharavi and his
relatives.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Assembly of Islamic Revolution, Iraq's biggest
Shiite opposition group, claimed the Iraqi government agents
buried Ayatollah Gharavi in Najaf secretly right after the
incident with an aim to prevent any possible protesting
demonstration, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 07:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Condemns Assassination of Shiite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei strongly condemned the assassination of a Shiite
religious leader in southern Iraq, warning that Iran can not
remain indifferent toward such crimes, Tehran Radio reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Khamenei as saying that the assassination of
two prominent Shiite scholars, Ayatollah Gharavi and Ayatollah
Sheikh Morteza Boroujerdi, within two months indicated the
"malicious plots of enemies" against the Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei issued the statement after Gharavi, along with his
driver, one of his sons and his son-in-law, was killed by
unidentified gunmen Thursday night in Najaf, a Shiite Muslim holy
place in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Gharavi was the second Shiite leader murdered in Najaf in the
past two months following the April 22 killing of Ayatollah
Boroujerdi.
</P>
<P>
"The great Iranian nation and the whole world of Shiite
Muslims can not show indifference towards such crimes," Khamenei
said, describing Gharavi as one of the top Shiite religious
scholars.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leader called on the Iraqi government to seriously
deal with the two assassinations and to carry out its
"international and human duties" in order to allay concerns of the
Iranian nation and Shiite Muslims worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry Director General for Persian Gulf
Affairs Ali Aghsar Hojji Saturday night summoned Iraqi charge
d'affaires in Tehran Saleh Noori Samarmad to lodge a strong
protest against the killings.
</P>
<P>
Hojji stressed that the Iraqi government has the responsibility
to safeguard the security of life and properties of Iranian
citizens in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He called on Baghdad to take necessary measures to punish those
responsible for the assassinations, warning that a repetition of
such incidents would have negative impact on the relations between
the two former enemies.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought a bloody war between 1980 and 1988 that
was triggered by territorial and religious dispute. Iraq is a
Sunni Muslim-dominated country, while Iran is largely a Shiite
Muslim country.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi envoy expressed regret over the incident and its
negative impact on the Iraqi-Iranian relations, saying he would
inform the Iraqi government of Iran's stance and would give a
relevant answer to Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
