<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt Pledges Support to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has said that his government is committed to fighting the
HIV/AIDS pandemic and that he will personally contribute to the
prevention and mitigation efforts of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said this in a speech read on his behalf by
Vice-President Christon Tembo on Friday night in Lusaka during
the launching of fund-raising campaign for Zambia's hosting of
the 11th International Conference on AIDS in Africa in September,
1999, according to Zambia Daily Mail published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has relentlessly fought to control the spread of AIDS
since 1986, said Chiluba, adding that his government will put in
its best in this regard.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the government's early responses to the
epidemic are predominantly bio-medical and health-focused in
approach.
</P>
<P>
"To a large extent, the social, cultural, political, economic
and other factors governing the spread of the epidemic were only
taken into account to a minimal extent in those early responses,"
said the president.
</P>
<P>
This has compelled the government to pursue a multi-sectoral
approach to the pandemic, which includes the prevention and
control of HIV/AIDS in the civil service program under the
multi-sectoral approach program launched in 1994, added Chiluba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
