<HEADLINE> Kenya to Collect Airport Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA)
will start collecting airport taxes from airlines from September,
in a bid to curb the mounting national budget deficit which
accounts 2.7 percent of the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The move follows an amendment to the Air Passenger Service
Charge Act in the Finance Bill, said a report from the Daily
Nation newspaper Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Finance Bill, passengers on external journeys will
be required to pay 20 U.S. Dollars or the equivalent in Kenyan
Shillings to the airlines. Passengers on internal flights will
pay 100 Shillings (1.67 Dollars).
</P>
<P>
KRA Chairman Hilary Ng'weno revealed the news at the Indian
Ocean port of Mombasa on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he vowed to make efforts to improve the authority's
management and combat corruption.
</P>
<P>
"The KRA management is determined to eradicate graft and it is
going to do so by addressing legitimate cases brought to its
attention," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
