<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Urged to Cut Visa Charges to Revamp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is urged to
abolish visa fees for 12 months or reduce charges to 10 U.S.
Dollars to revamp the collapsing tourism.
</P>
<P>
The Mombasa and Coast Tourist Association (MCTA) is also
asking the government to suspend duty on jet fuel to encourage
more tourists to use chartered flights as the country's roads are
"in a deplorable state," local press reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
MCTA Chairman Najib Balala, also the Mayor of Mombasa which is
Kenya's commercial hub bordering the Indian Ocean, called on the
government to give landing rights to international flights to
Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Balala suggested the upgrading of the Malindi Airport at the
coast so that it can receive chartered-flight tourists.
</P>
<P>
Mombasa hoteliers called on the government last week to stop
protecting Kenya Airways from competition by barring
international flights into Mombasa as the airline is a private
firm.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's tourism industry went into free-fall in August last
year when killings and clashes erupted in Likoni area of Mombasa
and then spread to many parts of the coast region. Mombasa sees
more than 70 percent of tourists visiting Kenya every year.
</P>
<P>
"The government should set up a fund from which hotel and
restaurant owners can borrow during this difficult time," he
suggested, adding that the fund should be able to disburse soft
loans with an adequate repayment grace period.
</P>
<P>
He warned that many hotels are closing down with the excuse
that they are carrying out renovations, "but the underlying
factor is that they are experiencing low occupancy levels."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
