<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Loyalists Support Marcos' Burial at Heroes' Cemetery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of loyalists gathered
here Sunday to voice their support for the burial of former
President Ferdinand Marcos at the heroes' cemetery in Manila.
</P>
<P>
The supporters, converging Sunday afternoon on the back
entrance of the Philippine International Conference Center,
expressed their solid support for President-Elect Joseph Estrada's
plan to bury Marcos.
</P>
<P>
They displayed millions of signatures they have already
collected in support of Estrada's decision.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who would assume the presidency on June 30, stood firm
on his decision of interring Marcos' remains at the cemetery
despite protests from the opponents.
</P>
<P>
He said Marcos should be buried at the cemetery which is
usually for war heroes and deceased presidents for his role in
fighting the Japanese invaders during the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
However, his plan drew protests from 28 groups including the
church, human rights victims and the business sector.
</P>
<P>
The opponents, led by former President Corazon Aquino, accused
Marcos of oppressing thousands of Filipinos and looting billions
of dollars' wealth from the state treasury.
</P>
<P>
The Marcos loyalists have finally decided to come out in the
open in face of the unrelenting attacks on the later president and
on the integrity of incoming President Estrada, the loyalists said
in a press release.
</P>
<P>
"Majority of Filipinos are in favor of this burial. We may not
have prominent personalities because we are mostly ordinary
Filipino citizens, but there are millions of us all over the
country. This debate might just provoke the rest of us to come out
publicly and express our sentiment," said Cherry Cobarrubias,
national chairman and spokesperson of the 4.5-million-strong
Marcos Loyalist Movement.
</P>
<P>
Marcos was ousted in a bloodless popular revolt in February
1986. He fled to Hawaii, the United States, where he died three
years later. His successor, Corazon Aquino, refused to allow the
return of his body to the country. In 1993, President Fidel Ramos
allowed the return, but refused to have him buried at the heroes'
cemetery with state honors.
</P>
<P>
Marcos' corpse is now inside a crystal sarcophagus in a crypt
at his hometown in the northern Philippines. He is expected to be
buried on July 11 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
