<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Striving to Resume Role of Far East Financial Center (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 21 (Xinhua) - Shanghai, known as "the Asia's Wall
Street" 60 years ago, is striving today to resume its role as a
financial, commercial and trade center in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
In internationalizing its finance sector, the Shanghai "Bund",
a tiny downtown area with no more than 1 square kilometers but used to
be home to 113 financial buildings, is again the focus of
attention of the world's financial industry.
</P>
<P>
Today, there are 51 overseas financial institutions, 163
representative offices of other such institutions, and their
combined assets reach 17.51 billion U.S. dollars, and they have
provided a total of 13.35 billion U.S. dollars of loans,
according to the Shanghai Branch of the People's Bank of China,
the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
That's a sharp increase from eight years ago, when there were
only four overseas banks in the city.
</P>
<P>
The CitiBank of the United States moved its China headquarters
from Hongkong to Shanghai in November 1994, indicating its
intention to expand business in China. It was soon followed by
other major banks of the world, including the British Standard
Charter Bank, the Shanghai and Hongkong Banking Corp.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, a pilot program was launched in Shanghai
allowing foreign banks to do the Chinese currency yuan-based
business. Nine overseas banks have so far been approved to do
the Renminbi-based business.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials in Shanghai said that this program has been
going on "smoothly" so far. And despite some rigorous restrictions
imposed on the Renminbi-based business, it marks the beginning of
China's internationalization process of its financial market.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials also disclosed that the authorities are
considering the new applications by other overseas banks for doing
such business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Striving to Resume Role of Far East Financial Center (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Shanghai Stock Exchange, the largest stock market in China,
has become a mature institution dealing treasury bonds, stocks and
investment funds. Its clout in the Chinese economy is being
further reinforced.
</P>
<P>
The other side of the Bund across the Yangtze River is now a
new financial center of this city, the Lujiazui Financial and
Trade Development District. In 1.7-square-km area, 20 high-rise
office buildings have just been erected, and other 10 are expected
to be completed in two years.
</P>
<P>
To build this city into a world economic, financial and trade
hub was the wish of the Late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, and
a strategic policy-decision of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
A high-ranking official from the People's Bank of China
Shanghai Branch said that Shanghai is going to follow
international norms in managing its financial institutions,
bringing in more overseas financial bodies. China is also planning
to set up a duty-free financial market in Shanghai, officials
disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
