<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Privatizes Two More Train Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Railway (BR)
authority will hand over operational management of two more train
services to private companies, as part of its privatization plan,
press reports here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The operational management of the two services -- Karnaphuli
Express and Balaka Express running on the Dhaka-Chittagong and the
Dhaka-Mymensingh routes respectively -- would be turned over to
two private companies which are scheduled to conduct commercial
operations from the first week of next month.
</P>
<P>
The two private agencies have already got work orders from the
BR, a senior BR official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The BR would supply fuel for the trains and appoint drivers and
guards after the services are transferred to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The lease holders would sell tickets and perform management
work with its own staff.
</P>
<P>
By so doing, the BR could earn on average 800,000 taka (about
17,400 U.S. dollars) per month from each of the two services,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Due to mismanagement, the Bangladesh's state-owned railway
sector has been suffering heavy losses in recent years. The
government has decided to allow the private sector to participate
in the operational management work in order to make railway
services profitable.
</P>
<P>
The service management of another railway express running on
the Dhaka-Chittagong route was handed over to a private company
early this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
