<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Sweeps Double Win in 100m and Long Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- World sprint queen Marion Jones
displayed a brilliant show Saturday night by sweeping the women's
100 meters and long jump titles at the U.S. Athletics
Championships in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old basketballer-turned-athlete, aiming to finish a
100m, 200m and long jump sweep, done only by Stella Walsh in 1948,
opened her race with a fabulous 10.72 second run in the 100
meters, and went on to take the long jump with a wind-aided 7.21
meters.
</P>
<P>
She wound up the day by finishing first in the 200m semifinal
with a time of 22.46. She needs to win the 200m final on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"She is one of the greatest female athletes ever to walk on
this planet," Jones' coach Trevor Graham said. "She is very
competitive, eager to learn and to understand her sport more. She
is going to be great in all three events in the next couple of
years."
</P>
<P>
In fact, Jones had promised to win as many as five gold medals
at the 2000 Olympic Games after she clocked the year's fastest
time 10.71 last month in China's Chengdu.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very excited with the time, but I thought I would run a
little faster," Jones said.
</P>
<P>
Jones only needed two jumps to seal the long jump title. She
got her winner in the opening round, and then fouled and passed
her final four leaps before racing to victory in the 200m heat.
</P>
<P>
The men's 100 meters final was marred by the withdrawl of
Maurice Greene, who said he suffered from stomach and leg cramps.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sad and disappointed. I had big plans for this
championship met. I misjudged the heat and my body's dehydrated
and keeps cramping up. I've depleted my body of all its
minerals. It wouldn't help the sport if I got out there and quit,"
said Greene, who hoped to beat the world record of 9.84 seconds
before the race.
</P>
<P>
1992 Olympic bronze medallist Dennis Mitchell also pulled out
the final due to a leg cramp. Tim Harden won the race with a
wind-aided 9.88, with Brian Lewis second at 9.98, and Tim
Montgomery third at 9.99.
</P>
<P>
The wind was 4.9 meters per second, well over the allowable 2.0
meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Mary Slaney pulled up with two laps remaining in the 5,000 with
a tendon injury to her lower right leg. The 39-year-old said:"I
head something pop. I can't put any weight on it."
</P>
<P>
Chris Huffins produced the best decathlon mark in the world
this year with a personal best 8,694 points. Bryan Bronson also
ran the fastest time in the world this year in the 400m hurdles
with a 47.81 in a semifinal heat.
</P>
<P>
Another world best this year came from the triple jump produced
by LaMark Carter, who bounced a 17.44 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
