<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Thai Youths Addicted to Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Students account for 24 percent of the 22,064 addicts who have
been treated at 284 rehabilitation centers since last October, the
ministry was quoted by Sunday's Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The number of youths being treated for heroin addiction was
higher than that for amphetamine.
</P>
<P>
A report by the ministry said that between October 1996 and
September 1997, 18.5 percent of the 38,895 addicts receiving
treatment are youths of an average age of 19.
</P>
<P>
Among them, amphetamine addiction was recorded at 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
From October last year to May this year, however, heroin
addiction among youngsters treated at the centers accounted for
64.8 percent, followed by amphetamine addiction, 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
Though appreciating cooperation from schools in testing the
urine of pupils, the Health Ministry urged schools to put emphasis
on "strengthening the spirit" of the students to resist drug use.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will conduct a nationwide campaign on June 27 and
28, focusing on the involvement of communities and families in
preventing drug use in children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
