<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Failure Plunges Bangladesh into Darkness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh was plunged into darkness
for several hours as the national power grid broke down Saturday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The national grid failed at 7:10 p.m. local time due to a
technical fault at a power plant which forced automatic shutdown
in all the major power generating unites in the country, official
sources were quoted Sunday by press reports here as saying.
</P>
<P>
All the country, including the capital city of Dhaka and the
southeastern port city of Chittagong, was immediately enveloped by
darkness.
</P>
<P>
At about 9 p.m., power generation was restored at some power
plants and power supply was partially resumed in the capital city,
but most parts of the country remained without power until
midnight.
</P>
<P>
This was the second national grid failure within three months
plunging the entire country into darkness for hours. Each time the
authorities concerned formed an inquiry committee to ascertain the
cause of the failure but so far no report of the committee has
been made public.
</P>
<P>
Life was made miserable on a hot and humid night without power,
and thousands of soccer fans demonstrated in different places of
the country as the power failure made it impossible for them to
watch the World Cup football matches on television, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina directed all the officials
concerned to get the power supply resumed at the earliest possible
time and State Minister for Energy Rafiqul Islam and senior
officials of the Power Development Board rushed to the load
dispatch center to monitor the repair work, according to the
reports.
</P>
<P>
Hasina took over the Energy Ministry earlier this year,
removing former Energy Minister Nooruddin Khan reportedly for his
failure to ensure normal power supply in the country.
</P>
<P>
The daily demand for power in Bangladesh is 2,200 megawatts
against a supply of 1,700 megawatts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Hospitals Asked to Reduce HIV Transmission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 21 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has asked
community hospitals to improve counseling services and treatment
for HIV-positive pregnant women in order to reduce perinatal
transmission from mothers to newborn babies.
</P>
<P>
Viput Poolcharoen, director of Thailand's Aids Division, said
the current counseling process provided in state hospitals needs
to be improved, according to Sunday's Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the most common problem observed is that
many counselors unwittingly informed husbands of pregnant women
that their wives are HIV-positive, without the women's will.
</P>
<P>
HIV is a virus which can cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
In many cases, it has also been observed that pregnant women
are HIV-positive while their husbands are free from the infection,
Viput noted.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted in the past two years by the Health
Department showed that the rate of HIV infection among pregnant
women whose husbands' HIV status was not known was as high as 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
Instead of the counselors informing the husbands of pregnant
women, Viput said, it would be best for them to ask the women to
convince their husbands to get themselves tested.
</P>
<P>
Apart from providing appropriate counseling, it is also
important for hospitals to provide anti-infection drugs to reduce
possible infection of HIV among the newborns, Viput said.
</P>
<P>
Since there is continuous change in the regimen of drugs and
the dosage recommended for preventing mother-child HIV
transmission, hospitals should be flexible and keep themselves
updated on the latest information.
</P>
<P>
The current regimen recommended by the Thai-U.S. Anti-HIV
Infection Center is a short course which can reduce
mother-to-child HIV transmission by two-thirds while a long-course
regimen recommended by a U.S. aids clinical group reduces
transmission by one-third.
</P>
<P>
Many hospitals in Thailand have been reportedly facing
difficulty in complying with both the short- and long-course
programs because of cash shortages to buy the expensive drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Evaluate, Reform Health Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will appoint a team of
experts to launch a year-long evaluation of its health systems and
propose recommendations for reform, the newspaper The Bangkok Post
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The project, part of the Asian Development Bank's structural
adjustment loan, is to begin this week. The evaluation results and
proposals will be presented by April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The four main areas to be evaluated by the technical
consultants are decentralization of health personnel, services
provided by state hospitals, hospital patients' referral system
and medical and health finance management.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a top Public Health Ministry official as
saying the experts should find a way to decentralize health
workers to areas with shortage problems.
</P>
<P>
The official also said hospital services should be made more
efficient with the emphasis on equality.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the discrepancy in social benefits for different
groups, which leads to unequal opportunity and different standards
of service quality in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Problems of overcrowding in big hospitals continued to exist
due to the current weak patients referral system, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he stressed that it is necessary for the experts to
consider social consequences of their recommendations in addition
to economic efficiency so as to ensure the proposed development
plan could be applied to the country's current social setting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans to Cut Production By 70 Million Tons in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to cut coal
production by 70 million tons this year to reduce the glut and
achieve the coal market balance, today's "China Daily"
(Business Weekly) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quoted an official with the
State Coal Industry Bureau as saying that the bureau is determined
to cut illegal and irrational coal output by 150 million tons in
the coming two or three years, which is an indispensable choice to
turn back the money-losing trend that has arisen in the sector
since the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, the key coal firms reported
deficits of 184.3 million US dollars, increasing losses of 209.6
million US dollars over the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The losses resulted from a sustained flagging market caused by
an astonishing glut of coal.
</P>
<P>
China boasts the largest coal producer in the world. It
produced 1.33 billion tons of coal and consumed 1.29 billion tons
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China's coal stockpiles are still over 130 million
tons, according to the China Coal News.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the serious glut to rampant production of
township and village coal mines.
</P>
<P>
China has 93 key state coal mines, 2,500 local state coal mines
and 75,000 township and village coal mines.
</P>
<P>
Last year, township and village coal mines produced 581 million
tons of coal, or 43.6 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government has strived to implement the Coal Law to
regulate the development of township and village coal mines since
December 1996 when the law officially took effort.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, coal producers should apply for a mine
license and production license from the government.
</P>
<P>
The State Coal Industry Bureau has made up its mind to rectify
the small coal mines completely this year, laying out a sound
foundation for the healthy development of the sector, the paper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
