<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Immunizes 16 Million Children Against Polio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Brazil launched a national
campaign of vaccination against polio Saturday.
</P>
<P>
More than 16 million children under the age of five were
immunized in the campaign launched by Brazilian Health Minister
Jose Serra in Sao Paulo, the largest city of the country.
</P>
<P>
People can see many posters with the picture of famous
Brazilian forward Ronaldo Luiz Nazario de Lima, who gestured the
children to go to the vaccination posts, and the slogan of "Brazil
Against Polio. We Are Going To Win the Game."
</P>
<P>
Serra said the campaign is fundamental to maintain the
eradication of polio from the country, which was certified in 1994
by the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian National Health Foundation distributed Saturday
30.9 million vaccine doses in some 131,000 vaccination posts
nationwide with about half a million people offering the service
and a budget of 24 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Serra said this is the first stage of the National Campaign of
Multivaccination, and that the second will be held on August 15
against diphtheria, tetanus, whooping cough, rubella, measles and
hepatitis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
