<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Official: Political Uncertainties Keep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 21 (Xinhua) -- An Indonesian government official
has warned that it will be difficult to attract foreign investors
to the country if political uncertainties still prevail.
</P>
<P>
"As long as the political problems have not yet been
definitively settled, Indonesia will be seen as a high risk
country (to invest)," Minister/State Secretary Akbar Tanjung said
here Saturday at a discussion on industrial reform.
</P>
<P>
The political uncertainties are also causing hesitation to
return to Indonesia among those Indonesians who have left the
country following the May 13-15 riots in Jakarta, capital of
Indonesia, the official Antara News Agency Sunday quoted Akbar as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's economic capabilities are now at their lowest and
the country badly needs foreign and domestic investors to come out
of its economic crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been hit by economic crisis since July last year.
The value of the rupiah, the national currency, has lost more than
80 percent against the U.S. dollar and the crisis caused political
uncertainties which forced former President Soeharto to step down
on May 21.
</P>
<P>
The most important thing the government is now trying to
accomplish is to ensure the availability of daily necessities to
the public at prices they can afford as a precondition to the
maintenance of political stability and law and order, Akbar noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an economic observer said the government will find
it difficult to stabilize the rupiah without confidence from home
and abroad in the country's political condition.
</P>
<P>
The plummeting of the exchange rate of the rupiah (15,000 per
dollar at present) is mainly caused by political uncertainty in
the country which has reduced confidence in the government, Marie
Pangestu of the Center for Strategic and International Studies
said.
</P>
<P>
The regional factor marked by the weakening of the Japanese yen
and the increasing demand for the U.S. dollar in the domestic
market for debt repayment also contributed to the rupiah's drop,
she added.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, we have to follow the flow of the market because the
rupiah will further weaken if the political uncertainty continues.
This is proven by the fact that the present government has not
been able to restore market confidence," she said.
</P>
<P>
She predicted that with an economic growth of minus 15 percent
this year, Indonesia would need seven to 10 years to restore the
economy to its level before the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
