<HEADLINE> Establishment of Financial Institution to Enhance Postal Savings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- China is promoting the
establishment of a financial institution to handle the country's
extensive postal savings business, according to today's "China
Daily" (Business Weekly).
</P>
<P>
"We want to set up the country's first nationwide financial
institution specialized in retail financial services," the English
newspaper quoted Tao Liming, director of the Postal Savings and
Remittance Bureau as saying.
</P>
<P>
The financial institution would be a subordinate of the State
Bureau of Posts, but its financial operations would be supervised
by the country's central bank, the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
The move will put the postal savings business under the
standardized operation and management of the financial sector,
hence settling a paradox as the country's laws do not allow
non-financial institutions to provide financial services.
</P>
<P>
It will also expand the business scope for postal savings to
include individual settlement, credit cards and financial
consultation.
</P>
<P>
At present, China has 79,000 postal offices, of which only
32,000 do the savings business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
