<HEADLINE> Social Democratic Party Wins in Czech Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- The Social Democratic Party won
32.35 percent of the votes in the parliamentary elections Friday
and Saturday, becoming the biggest party in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary results made public by the Central
Election Committee, the right Civic Democratic Party won 27.59
percent of the votes, followed by the Communist Party of the Czech
and Moravia with 11.09 percent.
</P>
<P>
Two other parties, People's Party and Liberal Party (Unie
Svobody) of the Christian Democratic Union also won the 5 percent
threshold needed for the 200-seat parliamentary representation,
with 9.13 and 8.54 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
The election was moved up for two years because of party
struggles. The parliament was elected on June 1996.
</P>
<P>
The victory of the Social Democratic Party was seen as a change
in the balance of political forces in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
