<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Exports Increase by 17.94 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican exports amounted to
1.7 billion U.S. dollars during the first five months of this
year, a 17.94 percent increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Data published by the Foreign Trade Ministry Saturday show that
53.8 percent of that total came from the export of industrial
products, 37.8 percent from agricultural products and 8.4 percent
from livestock and fishing products.
</P>
<P>
Coffee and bananas are the two main traditional exporting
products in this Central American country.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica exported 256 million dollars of coffee in
January-May, 39.6 percent more than the same period of 1997, and
245.44 million dollars of bananas with a 13.2 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
However the ministry said textile export was reduced by 4.3
percent to 294.88 million dollars in the period.
</P>
<P>
A foreign trade official said he expected a 10 percent rise in
the country's export this year to 5 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
