<HEADLINE> Jackson Keeps Lead at Women's Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- German Ina Teutenberg won the
road race to capture the fifth stage while Canadian Linda Jackson
retained her overall lead Saturday in the International women's
challenge cycling race in Boise Idaho of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Teutenberg led through the streets of the state capitol to win
the stage in one hour, 21 minutes and 26 seconds.
</P>
<P>
But no one gained time on pace-setter Jackson, who was 23rd
which was good enough to keep her overall lead entering the last
of six stages in the race
</P>
<P>
Jackson's overall time of 9:35:22 remained 50 seconds better
than Russia's Valentina Polkhanova.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania's Diana Ziliute moved to third and France's Jeannie
Longo rose to fourth after two Lithuanian rivals fell back. But
Ziliute stayed 1:15 off Jackson's pace with Longo another seven
seconds behind her.
</P>
<P>
Teutenberg edged compatriot Petra Rossner and American Karen
Livington at the finish to win the stage. Longo was 27th in the
criterium stage.
</P>
<P>
The independent stage race is a special event with 100,000
U.S. Dollars in prize money, luring a top international women's
field to the Rocky Mountains of the western United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
