</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Visit Called "Very Important" for Bilateral Trade Ties -1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
upcoming visit to China is "very important" for the development of
U.S.-China economic and trade relations, said Alan Turley,
minister counselor of commercial affairs at the U.S. Embassy in
Beijing, in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Turley, who noted that this is the first visit to China by a
U.S. president in almost 10 years, said the trip will help solve
many problems and reduce misunderstandings between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Noting that U.S.-China relations are multi-faceted and include
many issues, Turley said that both sides can continue to work
together in agreed-upon areas, and conduct "friendly and frank"
discussions on those issues on which they cannot reach agreement
such as human rights, MFN (most-favored-nation) status for China
and defense.
</P>
<P>
He said people should understand that bilateral relations are
complicated and will never be perfect, and that there will
continue to be disagreements, which will not affect the
fundamental interests of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He added that in the past two decades bilateral economic and
trade relations have grown rapidly and U.S. statistics show that
bilateral trade volume last year reached 60 billion U.S. dollars
and many U.S. companies, including many transnationals, have
invested in China.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the bilateral trade imbalance, Turley said that the
United States hopes to redress the imbalance through expanding
exports to China while avoiding cutbacks in imports from China,
adding that the U.S. stance is that such a cut-off would be
harmful to both countries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese statistics show that bilateral trade volume last year
was 49 billion U.S. dollars with the United States becoming
China's second largest trade partner and China the fourth largest
for the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Visit Called "Very Important" for Bilateral Trade Ties-2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese side repeatedly stressed that it will strive to
expand bilateral trade, especially increasing its imports from the
United States while hoping that the United States can make efforts
in return to lift its export restrictions and offer credit support
for its companies.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether bilateral hi-tech cooperation would help
redress the imbalance, Turley said it certainly would be helpful.
</P>
<P>
During the short period of two years since he came to China,
Turley has contacted many U.S. business people who are interested
in investing in almost every aspect of the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
Saying that the United States views China as a huge potential
market, Turley said he believes that there is great potential for
U.S. businesses to invest in China's transportation
infrastructure, construction, and transportation equipment such as
airplanes and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
On the MFN issue, Turley said that the U.S. government's
position properly separates human rights from the annual renewal
of China's MFN trading status.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has always supported and will continue to
support MFN trading status for China, he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
On the protection of intellectual property rights, he said that
the attitude change of the two sides shows interesting progress,
adding that the United States is aware of the strong effort made by
the Chinese government to clean up those plants involved in piracy.
</P>
<P>
He also said the United States is willing to show and has shown
great flexibility during negotiations on China's entry into the
World Trade Organization, and it will continue to show flexibility
in some aspects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
