<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Planning Extensive "Seabed Forests" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 21 (Xinhua) -- Zeng Chengkui, a prominent Chinese
oceanographer with the Chinese Academy of Sciences, has proposed
that China build "seabed forests" similar to planting trees on
land to save the deteriorating marine environment.
</P>
<P>
This seaweed could absorb carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and
phosphorus compounds that come from marine animals and give off
oxygen that they need, Zeng explained.
</P>
<P>
The seabed forest could also purify and improve the
environment, he said, using the island county of Changdao in
Shandong Province, east China, as an example, where a
10-nautical-mile by 10-meter corridor of seaweed and kelp is
growing offshore. This seaweed forest is a promising residence for
various marine organisms.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, a hectare of sea produces ten times
the profit of a hectare on land. Changdao has a 47,000 ha. "blue
pasture" that is home to abalone, scallops and kelp.
</P>
<P>
Changdao's experience has shown that a seabed forest can cut
the effect of waves and offer abundant food and shelter for marine
animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980621.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Withdraws from U.S. 100m Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Maurice Greene, chasing the
100-meter world record, quited the 100m finals at the United
States Athletics Championships in New Orleans of Louisianah with
cramps.
</P>
<P>
Tim Harden won in a wind-aided 9.89 seconds after Greene
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
One of Greene's earlier efforts was a wind-aided 9.84-second
run that would have matched the world record set by Canada's
Donovan Bailey at the 1996 Olympics had it not been for the
excessive tailwind.
</P>
<P>
Greene said he had stomach cramps and diarrhea. "Everything I
put into my body went back out," Greene said.
</P>
<P>
Greene had a wind-aided 9.79-second run last month at Eugene,
Oregon. His training partner and main rival, Trinidad's Ato
Boldon, ran two 9.86s in Athens this week and Greene had hoped to
crack the mark here.
</P>
<P>
Greene, who made his decision one hour before the race, said he
will be fit and ready for next month's Goodwill Games in New York,
where he will face Boldon and Bailey to decide who is the world's
best sprinter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
