<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts and Figures of World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Following are the facts and figures
of Saturday's matches at the World Cup finals:
</P>
<P>
A total of 10 goals were scored in the three games on Saturday,
the most goals on a single day at the current finals. Only one
goal was netted the day before on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Netherlands' 5-0 route over South Korea recorded the biggest
win of the finals so far. Five different Dutch players getting
their names on the scoresheet. It was their biggest ever win at
the finals and the first time the Dutch had scored five since
beating Austria 5-1 in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Bergkamp, who scored the third Dutch goal, has netted in
each of the last four matches he has started in the finals. He
scored in the Netherlands' last three matches in 1994 against
Morocco, Ireland and Brazil at the U.S. finals. He failed to score
against Belgium in his team's opening match in France but came on
as substitute in that game.
</P>
<P>
It was South Korea's heaviest defeat since 1954 when they lost
9-0 to Hungary and 7-0 to Turkey on their World Cup debut.
</P>
<P>
Asian teams have fared disastrously in France. The record now
reads played seven, lost seven, goals for 1, goals against 16. The
only two teams definitely eliminated so far are Asian -- South
Korea and Saudi Arabia. Japan, beaten 1-0 by Croatia, have also
lost twice without scoring and look sure to go out.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, the first team at the finals to fight back from a
two-goal deficit, drew 2-2 with Belgium and have lost only once in
eight matches against European opponents at the finals in the last
20 years. The only team to beat them was Norway in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Despite throwing away their advantage, Belgium did at least
manage a first draw with Mexico following defeats to the Mexican
hosts in the 1970 (0-1) and 1986 finals (1-2).
</P>
<P>
World Cup newcomers Croatia completed a second consecutive win
over fellow-debutants. Their victory over Japan followed a 3-1
triumph over Jamaica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
