<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, June 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- European Union's Mideast peace envoy Miguel Angel
Moratinos Saturday called for working out a new strategy to get
the peace process out of its stalemate.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference after his meeting with Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouq al-Sharaa, the EU official stressed the importance
of consultations between the EU and the Arab countries to find out
a formula to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said he discussed with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad the
latest developments of the peace process and the grave deadlock it
arrived at due to the intransigent policies of the Israeli
government.(BC-Syria-EU Envoy)
----
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab League Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid
Saturday expressed welcome to European Union's stance on the Arab
and Palestinian cause in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I consider this stance is very supportive of the Arab and
Palestinian stance," Abdel-Meguid said in an interview with
Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on a statement issued by the EU at the end of
a summit in Britain, which voiced "very grave concern" over the
stalemate in Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.(BC-Egypt-Arab
League-EU )
----
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh Saturday
reiterated support for all efforts aimed at stopping the armed
conflicts between Eritrea and Ethiopia, the Yemeni News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Libyan Secretary of Arab Unity Gomaa
al-Mahdi al Fazani, Saleh called on Eritrea and Ethiopia to solve
their border disputes through peaceful means to avoid the dangers
and miseries caused by war.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan official arrived here on Friday for a two-day
visit. During the meeting, he briefed Saleh on the initiative
offered by Libya on behalf of the Saharan countries to solve the
conflicts between Eritrea and Ethiopian.(BC-Yemen-Ethiopia )
----
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt said Saturday that it will cut oil output by
20,000 barrels per day as of July 1 in a bid to help stabilize the
world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdi Ali Abdel Wahab Al-Banbi said that
his country will reduce the output to 830,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Though Egypt is not a member of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), the planned cut is aimed at supporting
the efforts made by OPEC members, Al-Banbi said.(BC-Egypt-Oil-Cut)
----
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq announced on Saturday that it
accepts a recent resolution of the United Nations Security Council
on buying spare parts for its oil sector.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Foreign Ministry told the official Iraqi
News Agency that "Iraq will deal with the Security Council
resolution No. 1175 of 1998" as a program of action for a period
of 120 days.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution which was passed on Friday, Iraq is
allowed to spend 300 million U.S. dollars of the oil-for-food
program revenues to buy spare parts badly needed in its oil
industry.(BC-Iraq-UN-Resolution)
----
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Georgian-Abkhazian talks have
achieved certain progress, the Interfax news agency reported from
Tibilisi, capital of Georgia, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze and Abkhazian leader
Vladislav Ardzinba will meet in the near future and sign documents
on a settlement of the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict, Executive
Secretary of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), Boris
Berezovsky said Friday in Tibilisi.(BC-Georgia-Abkhazia-Talks )
nnnn
</P>
